Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @pak choi{1}(trimmed and thinly sliced widthways), then thinly slice widthways. Trim and halve the @green beans{80%g}(trimmed and halved).

Zest and halve the @lime{1}(zested and halved).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on high heat. Drain the @king prawns{150%g}(drained).

Once hot, add the @sliced mushrooms{120%g} to the pan and fry, stirring occasionally, until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Halfway through cooking the mushrooms, add the prawns to the pan and fry for the remaining time, ~{2-3%minutes}. 

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw prawns.

Stir the @red Thai style paste{75%g}, @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) and garlic into the mushrooms.

Stir fry for ~{1%minute}.

Pour the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @soy sauce{25%ml}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{200%ml} into the pan.

> See pantry for water amount.

Bring to the boil, then add the green beans and the pak choi. Simmer until the prawns are cooked, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Cook so they're opaque in the middle.

Add the @udon noodles{220%g} to the soup and cook until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Remove the pan from the heat. Stir in the lime zest and half of the lime juice.

Taste the soup and add more @salt{}, @pepper{}, lime juice or sugar if needed.

Share the prawn udon noodle soup between your #bowls{}.

Cut any remaining lime into wedges for squeezing over.

Enjoy!